




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asset Pricing with Heterogeneous Consumers
AU  - Constantinides, George M.
AU  - Duffie, Darrell
Y1  - 1996/04/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262023
DO  - 10.1086/262023
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 219
EP  - 240
VL  - 104
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Empirical difficulties encountered by representative-consumer models are resolved in an economy with heterogeneity in the form of uninsurable, persistent, and heteroscedastic labor income shocks. Given the joint process of arbitrage-free asset prices, dividends, and aggregate income, satisfying a certain joint restriction, it is shown that this process is supported in the equilibrium of an economy with judiciously modeled income heterogeneity. The Euler equations of consumption in a representative-agent economy are replaced by a set of Euler equations that depend not only on the per capita consumption growth but also on the cross-sectional variance of the individual consumers' consumption growth.
AB  - Empirical difficulties encountered by representative-consumer models are resolved in an economy with heterogeneity in the form of uninsurable, persistent, and heteroscedastic labor income shocks. Given the joint process of arbitrage-free asset prices, dividends, and aggregate income, satisfying a certain joint restriction, it is shown that this process is supported in the equilibrium of an economy with judiciously modeled income heterogeneity. The Euler equations of consumption in a representative-agent economy are replaced by a set of Euler equations that depend not only on the per capita consumption growth but also on the cross-sectional variance of the individual consumers' consumption growth.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262023
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262023
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Localized Competition and the Aggregation of Plant-Level Increasing Returns: Blast Furnaces, 1929-1935
AU  - Bertin, Amy L.
AU  - Bresnahan, Timothy F.
Y1  - 1996/04/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262024
DO  - 10.1086/262024
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 241
EP  - 266
VL  - 104
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A recent empirical literature has shaken economists' confidence in the value of aggregate (industry-level) data to illuminate production relationships. But the statistical finding "you cannot aggregate," however well documented, is not an economic explanation. Plant-level relationships do aggregate in Depression-era blast furnace operations despite the presence of very substantial interplant heterogeneity, the most common economic cause of nonaggregability. The economic explanation of this lies in poor short-run substitutability of one plant's output for another's. Substitutability determines the importance of composition effects in understanding aggregate time series, constrains the potential cleansing effects of recessions, and therefore influences industry evolution quite broadly.
AB  - A recent empirical literature has shaken economists' confidence in the value of aggregate (industry-level) data to illuminate production relationships. But the statistical finding "you cannot aggregate," however well documented, is not an economic explanation. Plant-level relationships do aggregate in Depression-era blast furnace operations despite the presence of very substantial interplant heterogeneity, the most common economic cause of nonaggregability. The economic explanation of this lies in poor short-run substitutability of one plant's output for another's. Substitutability determines the importance of composition effects in understanding aggregate time series, constrains the potential cleansing effects of recessions, and therefore influences industry evolution quite broadly.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262024
Y2  - 2024/03/22
